cture></a></figure><h2><strong>The gap tends to widen when we adjust for protein</strong></h2><p>The comparison above looked at the cost <em>per kilogram</em>.</p><p>But we might also want to adjust for protein content: what’s the cheapest way to get enough protein?</p><p>I recalculated these numbers as the price <em>per 100 grams of protein</em>. The results are in the chart below. Again, here’s <a href="https://public.flourish.studio/visualisation/15317477/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">an interactive version</a> to explore.</p><p>Overall, the picture tends to look a bit worse for meat substitutes because they often have a slightly lower protein content. Sausages and chicken lose quite a bit of ground.</p><p>The exception to this is mince, where the Tesco unbranded version competes well with the meaty equivalent.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F53059f7f-3fa8-46c8-964c-0c9698465c01_1128x650.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RQ5_- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/M_7jhHu8M_cF2oxRZcyMeTqJ12h_exKdFGCZCl_0uRk=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY1MzA1OWY3Zi0zZmE4LTQ2YzgtOTY0Yy0wYzk2OTg0NjVjMDFfMTEyOHg2NTAucG5n 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/08SO0PFSe-5S3Ro0OVxI4ZOJhhvl- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RPbmbe16frZyhBDSG1VFFKcB9XeRBfOSk1lE3FV_Ut0=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY1MzA1OWY3Zi0zZmE4LTQ2YzgtOTY0Yy0wYzk2OTg0NjVjMDFfMTEyOHg2NTAucG5n 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/rNA-BJMIcstWAvh0iBHm4lnzXtaj2_aByDXxy9Ma1lU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY1MzA1OWY3Zi0zZmE4LTQ2YzgtOTY0Yy0wYzk2OTg0NjVjMDFfMTEyOHg2NTAucG5n 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/0-11xoBAuI- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a></figure><p>To complete the lot, I also calculated these prices per 1000 kilocalories. The gap actually closes a bit when adjusted for calories.</p><p>Here’s the <a href="https://public.flourish.studio/visualisation/15317522/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">interactive version</a> to explore.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d6a3792-0afe-4362-8f1b-7a5b9c9d45d1_1076x650.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/FLbE9OSm6Rx5uteVR2E7BQTpmBo2QHT4i1uCc_KiSZQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY2ZDZhMzc5Mi0wYWZlLTQzNjItOGYxYi03YTViOWM5ZDQ1ZDFfMTA3Nng2NTAucG5n 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/zrbUV_YKYf5gFU5_sMD7_wWMdyGCtQajra0dCKVtI_Y=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY2ZDZhMzc5Mi0wYWZlLTQzNjItOGYxYi03YTViOWM5ZDQ1ZDFfMTA3Nng2NTAucG5n 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/vjG6_ 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/dGhgbggg_j-pCqlYkl3UP-" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/gnnK5Qb3mpMJ5ZVSJ36m- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/QOTkcPHu-NqF06eBJ9EFrZhw0lmNmOaqi_RGY-_wvoQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY2ZDZhMzc5Mi0wYWZlLTQzNjItOGYxYi03YTViOWM5ZDQ1ZDFfMTA3Nng2NTAucG5n 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/O5Yr2KbL8gDI52XcYqw- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/dGhgbggg_j-pCqlYkl3UP- 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a></figure><h2><strong>Meat substitutes don’t just need to be cost-competitive: they need to be much cheaper</strong></h2><p>Full disclosure: I’m a big fan of meat substitutes. I’m happy to pay a bit more, and I am in a privileged position to do so.</p><p>But most people will not pay more for a product that they’re on-the-fence about. They probably won’t even make the switch if these products are the <em>same</em> price. Meat substitutes need to be quite clearly cheaper, especially if we want them to break into middle- and low-income markets.</p><p>How do we do that?</p><p>There are two options to change the price differential: make meat more expensive, or meat substitutes cheaper.</p><p>On the former, governments could implement a ‘meat tax’. The point of that being that the total cost of meat – in terms of its environmental and social costs – is not reflected in the market price. A tax would try to capture at least some of these ‘externalities’. Seems rational, but would be a bold step for a government to take.</p><p>The latter is harder to comment on without good cost breakdowns for meat substitutes. What costs so much: the ingredients, the energy for processing, is it a problem of scale? Some meat substitutes <em>seem</em> like they should be relatively cheap to make: we’re not talking about lab-grown meat here, we’re talking about turning pea, soy, or wheat protein into a patty. Maybe I’m underestimating the costs involved: a full breakdown would be useful to see which levers can be pulled to get them down.</p><p>While this might seem like a post against meat substitutes, I’m actually very bullish on them. They seem like the most credible pathway to reducing global meat consumption – the emissions, land use, deforestation, water use, and animal pain that comes with it.</p><p>But to succeed, they need to be much cheaper than they are today.</p><p><a href="https://amzn.to/3MdaOci" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Pre-order my forthcoming book</a></p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F112cef2d-7712-4f79-bee6-12be05e4ae46_1100x220.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_x3G0nf3m1DToXqM5HImBX3- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/-hj4gU5fmCNJ2sqsKAb9cO0- 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/8CgSCCEP4XVVTuDFztx-Wtkot23NscxpomsfgY_6_9M=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMTEyY2VmMmQtNzcxMi00Zjc5LWJlZTYtMTJiZTA1ZTRhZTQ2XzExMDB4MjIwLnBuZw==" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/mnzUxuiBS7f1rXqE32Cye6QNTJZ_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/8CgSCCEP4XVVTuDFztx-Wtkot23NscxpomsfgY_6_9M=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMTEyY2VmMmQtNzcxMi00Zjc5LWJlZTYtMTJiZTA1ZTRhZTQ2XzExMDB4MjIwLnBuZw== 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a></figure><a id="footnote-1" href="#footnote-anchor-1">1</a><p>In case it’s not obvious: I&#39;m not talking about reducing meat consumption of those in the poorest countries, where they consume little, and it&#39;s often crucial for nutrition.<br/><br/>The onus needs to come from richer countries where meat consumption per person is 10 to 20 times as high as those in poorer countries.<br/><br/><a href="https://ourworldindata.org/grapher/meat-supply-per-person" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">https://ourworldindata.org/grapher/meat-supply-per-person</a></p><p></p><a id="footnote-2" href="#footnote-anchor-2">2</a><p>As I covered in an <a href="https://ourworldindata.org/food-emissions-carbon-budget" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">older article</a>, a shift to a plant-based diet is the most effective way to reduce the carbon footprint of your diet.</p><p>Clark, Michael A., Nina GG Domingo, Kimberly Colgan, Sumil K. Thakrar, David Tilman, John Lynch, Inês L. Azevedo, and Jason D. Hill. &#34;Global food system emissions could preclude achieving the 1.5° and 2° C climate change targets.&#34; Science 370, no. 6517 (2020): 705-708.</p>